<seg id="1">what really goes on at inspections</seg>
<seg id="2">It would seem that many buyers, sellers, agents and neighbours have experienced some degree of open-house hysteria.</seg>
<seg id="3">Photo: Fiona Morris</seg>
<seg id="4">For all the neatly angled flags, shining A-frame notices and freshly-stocked clipboards, the urban warfare of the Sydney open-house inspection has a slyly winking underbelly.</seg>
<seg id="5">Throwing the doors of our most valuable properties open to Joe Public has a way of bringing about the baddest of bad behaviour, from neighbourly sabotage to staged lunacy.</seg>
<seg id="6">Add to that the litany of minor accident booby-traps, alarm debacles and fiendish take-no-prisoners buying strategy, and the Saturday morning house-viewing session is ripe for drama - or slapstick at the very least.</seg>
<seg id="7">Those who should know how to avoid this better than anyone are the estate agents themselves.</seg>
<seg id="8">Illustration: Cathy Wilcox</seg>
<seg id="9">One big operator in Sydney's blink-and-you're-gazumped property landscape laughs as he recalls a colleague's unfortunate first day on the job.</seg>
<seg id="10">It's this guy's first open inspection, he's got it all happening, the car's cleaned, brochures ready, clipboards ready.</seg>
<seg id="11">Achingly keen to please, the youngster bounds upstairs to check all is in place, connects with a low beam and half knocks himself out.</seg>
<seg id="12">The door bell rings and he's standing there with blood trickling down his head ... He left in an ambulance.</seg>
<seg id="13">BresicWhitney director Adrian Oddi can only feel for the agent who turned up early to an open house in the inner west and, feeling a little frazzled, took a rest on the couch.</seg>
<seg id="14">He woke up half an hour later to a handwritten message on the coffee table: 'You looked tired, didn't want to wake you.</seg>
<seg id="15">I'm interested, so please give me a call."'</seg>
<seg id="16">Then there are the punters, from the voyeurs to the tyre-kickers.</seg>
<seg id="17">Take the eastern suburbs woman who recognised pictures and trophies from a rival school to her son's.</seg>
<seg id="18">She realised the resident boy had the medal for beating her son at a high-level inter-school final.</seg>
<seg id="19">She was tempted to steal the keepsake, but held back.</seg>
<seg id="20">Another recalls seeing framed photos of a former partner, and one buyer in Darlinghurst can't forget the time she was greeted with a sex swing.</seg>
<seg id="21">And let's not forget the inevitable calls of nature, a scatalogical stone best left unturned.</seg>
<seg id="22">Brad Pillinger, an estate agent since 1989, says the real fun begins when disgruntled tenants are involved in a sale.</seg>
<seg id="23">In one case of a flooded garden, "they 'accidentally' left the hose on outside"; pretended they weren't home - "I loudly declared I'd have to climb in through the window, and, suddenly, they miraculously 'heard' the doorbell," he said.</seg>
<seg id="24">One agent tells of his associate calling him after walking in on a couple in flagrante delicto.</seg>
<seg id="25">"He's having a conversation with the guy while they're there, naked, like nothing was going on," he recalls.</seg>
<seg id="26">I'll never forget that phone call.</seg>
<seg id="27">But thefts during open houses, it seems, have dwindled to an urban myth.</seg>
<seg id="28">The only post-inspection allegation of theft one agent said he had encountered was a tenant complaining that his marijuana had been pilfered.</seg>
<seg id="29">The police weren't called.</seg>
<seg id="30">Nothing, however, beats the odd moment of amateur dramatics.</seg>
<seg id="31">"There was a house in Rozelle that had a shared driveway," recounts an inner west agent.</seg>
<seg id="32">"The neighbour of the vendor would walk up and down the driveway and act a little bit loony, jump around and tell people 'You know this is mine, I can do anything I like."'</seg>
<seg id="33">He soon received a letter from a solicitor, threatening to sue him for the difference in house price and value should his behaviour affect the sale.</seg>
<seg id="34">We never heard from him again.</seg>
<seg id="35">And there isn't an agent or experienced seller in the land who is unfamiliar with the age-old trick of artful dissuasion.</seg>
<seg id="36">Lucy Macken, Title Deeds scribe at Fairfax Media's Domain, has heard every line in the book.</seg>
<seg id="37">"People who want to buy it often talk it down," she says.</seg>
<seg id="38">Look at these glass balustrades, oh, they're bad for kids.</seg>
<seg id="39">We'd have to spend a fortune on new windows/soundproofing/guttering.</seg>
</doc>
