<seg id="1">Kyle Sandilands and Jackie O leaving 2Day FM</seg>
<seg id="2">Kyle and Jackie O departure 'amicable'</seg>
<seg id="3">Kyle Sandliands and Jackie O have turned down 'a nice deal' to continue their breakfast show and are leaving 2Day FM after more than a decade on air together.</seg>
<seg id="4">Vision: Southern Cross Austereo</seg>
<seg id="5">PT1M59Shttp://www.smh.com.au/action/externalEmbeddedPlayer?id=d-2wol8620349November 1, 2013 - 11:50AM</seg>
<seg id="6">Kyle Sandilands and Jackie O are leaving 2Day FM at the end of the year after more than a decade on air together, Southern Cross Australia has announced.</seg>
<seg id="7">Contract negotiations between Australia's most successful FM radio duo have collapsed, with the pair not returning to the Austereo network in 2014, bringing to an end a decade of ratings dominance.</seg>
<seg id="8">Calling it quits: Kyle Sandilands and Jackie O. Photo: Lee Besford</seg>
<seg id="9">In a statement issued by the broadcaster on Friday morning, Southern Cross Austereo head of content Craig Bruce said: "We're proud that Kyle and Jackie have not only given Sydney radio audiences the most entertaining radio show ever, they have also raised millions of dollars for charities and those in need whilst also enthralling listeners with the world's hottest music artists and exclusive interviews with famous Hollywood celebrities.</seg>
<seg id="10">"They have certainly lived up to their show mantra "Breakfast with the Stars.""</seg>
<seg id="11">None of which could have happened without the strong and dedicated team working hard behind the scenes.</seg>
<seg id="12">There have been rumours that management for Sandilands and Jackie O (real name Henderson) had been locked in heated negotiations for the past two months as the pair attempted to increase their already significant pay deals with Southern Cross.</seg>
<seg id="13">However, recent years of controversy and increased frustration between management and the duo, particularly Sandilands, resulted in the contract impasse, culminating in this morning's announcement.</seg>
<seg id="14">Their final show on the network is scheduled for November 29.</seg>
<seg id="15">A source close to the negotiations told Private Sydney this morning: "Kyle and Jackie were getting very frustrated by the negotiations."</seg>
<seg id="16">They were still football fields apart from each other after weeks of talks ... the weird thing is, I don't think they have any other place to go.</seg>
<seg id="17">Steve Allen, director of Fusion Strategy media marketing consultancy, said the show was the largest revenue generator in Australian radio, even eclipsing Alan Jones on 2GB, despite Jones having a larger audience.</seg>
<seg id="18">"Jones' audience isn't as attractive to advertisers as the ones tuning in to Kyle and Jackie O," Allen explained.</seg>
<seg id="19">Around $30 million worth of advertising a year is pumped into the show, according to research conducted by Fusion Strategy.</seg>
<seg id="20">"Advertisers are keen to target the youth market because they are considered a lucrative sector given their high discretionary income," Allen said.</seg>
<seg id="21">The pair also rank among the highest-paid voices on radio, their contracts worth around $1 million each, though heavy with bonus deals delivering lucrative incentives if the pair reach or improve on ratings targets.</seg>
<seg id="22">Southern Cross Austereo spokeswoman Lisa Schillaci says the network hasn't yet considered who might replace the popular breakfast duo.</seg>
</doc>
