<seg id="1">Father who looks at baby daughter he adores and aches for her lost twin</seg>
<seg id="2">By Ben Falk</seg>
<seg id="3">The cursor blinked on the computer screen, as I sat staring blankly at my emails.</seg>
<seg id="4">Earlier that day, I had returned from yet another scan with my wife, Christina, who was 32 weeks pregnant with our twin daughters.</seg>
<seg id="5">It had been a troubled pregnancy, and we had long prayed that this moment would never come.</seg>
<seg id="6">But now it was time to convey to our friends the most heartbreaking news - one of our babies had died.</seg>
<seg id="7">We had already told our family and closest friends in a series of shattering phone calls.</seg>
<seg id="8">And though it felt impersonal to send an email to others, we were emotionally exhausted and couldn't bear to keep repeating aloud the details of our sorrow.</seg>
<seg id="9">Ben Falk, with wife Christina and daughter Hannah, says he felt helpless and all he could do was try to be supportive and not fuss during the difficult pregnancy</seg>
<seg id="10">That evening, as I attempted to make supper, I broke down and sobbed into Christina's shoulder as she calmly stroked my head.</seg>
<seg id="11">Her strength then - as now - had been superhuman.</seg>
<seg id="12">That bleak day seemed such a stark contrast to the joyous one six months previously when we'd been excitedly telling friends our happy news.</seg>
<seg id="13">Losing a child in the womb is virtually impossible for any parent to bear, especially the mother.</seg>
<seg id="14">For fathers, though, it is a singular sort of grief.</seg>
<seg id="15">Physically detached from the baby, but just as desperate to feel and understand every stage of the pregnancy, it is hard for a man to process that a child that was once there, is gone.</seg>
<seg id="16">It was, without doubt, the worst experience of my life.</seg>
<seg id="17">Christina and I had been trying for children for more than three years.</seg>
<seg id="18">We'd met at a mutual friend's Christmas party in 2008 and were engaged nine months later.</seg>
<seg id="19">On Valentine's Day 2010, five months before our wedding, we decided Christina would come off the Pill.</seg>
<seg id="20">We dreamed of being able to stand up at the wedding and announce we were expecting.</seg>
<seg id="21">How naive we were.</seg>
<seg id="22">Christina simply couldn't get pregnant.</seg>
<seg id="23">We assumed it would happen fast, but it didn't.</seg>
<seg id="24">We still don't know why.</seg>
<seg id="25">Hannah Valentine Emilie Falk arrived just after 5pm on Wednesday June 12, weighing 7¿lbs.</seg>
<seg id="26">We¿d named her long ago, just as we had her sister, who we called Rose</seg>
<seg id="27">So when, in September 2012, Christina came into our bedroom to tell me her pregnancy test was positive, I didn't believe her, even asking her to take it again.</seg>
<seg id="28">She did so the next day, and it was still positive.</seg>
<seg id="29">We were ecstatic.</seg>
<seg id="30">We were even more thrilled when at our ten-week scan (we were scanned early because of our problems conceiving) we saw two little heartbeats on the monitor.</seg>
<seg id="31">Not only this, but our twins were identical (monochorionic, meaning they were sharing a placenta).</seg>
<seg id="32">We were stunned.</seg>
<seg id="33">In our most wistful moments, we had spoken of wanting a family with two children.</seg>
<seg id="34">And after so long, here we were with all our dreams coming true at once.</seg>
<seg id="35">The timing seemed perfect.</seg>
<seg id="36">I was 37, we owned our North London home, we were happy in our jobs - I'm a writer and Christina, 34, is an archive producer - and we had a great circle of friends.</seg>
<seg id="37">And then things started to go wrong.</seg>
<seg id="38">When we returned to our local Whittington Hospital for a scan at 16 weeks, the obstetrician performing the procedure told us of complications that could occur with identical twins.</seg>
<seg id="39">Because Hannah was very ill, Christina only got to hold her for a brief time before she was rushed off to the neonatal intensive care baby unit</seg>
<seg id="40">"I'm afraid one of the babies is pushed right to the top corner of Christina's womb and has minimal amniotic fluid," she said.</seg>
<seg id="41">I'm afraid it's twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome [TTTS].</seg>
<seg id="42">This was a disorder that can affect monochorionic twins.</seg>
<seg id="43">The obstetrician explained that one baby was unknowingly taking nutrients and blood from the other in the womb.</seg>
<seg id="44">TTTS means that the twins are disproportionate in size.</seg>
<seg id="45">A myriad other medical issues can also arise, such as heart conditions in the larger baby.</seg>
<seg id="46">Many twins who share a placenta don't get TTTS at all.</seg>
<seg id="47">Some get it late in the pregnancy when it doesn't particularly matter.</seg>
<seg id="48">But some cases are incredibly serious.</seg>
<seg id="49">This was the case with our children.</seg>
<seg id="50">Their TTTS was severe.</seg>
<seg id="51">I gripped Christina's hand tightly.</seg>
<seg id="52">One moment, we'd been thinking about baby names, the next we were told both of our children might die.</seg>
<seg id="53">Our best chance was to have laser surgery immediately to split the placenta, hopefully meaning that both babies could develop independently.</seg>
<seg id="54">Without it, there was a 90 per cent chance both babies would never be born.</seg>
<seg id="55">Even with it, there was only a 30 per cent chance that both would survive.</seg>
<seg id="56">I did what I normally do when in shock - started making lists about what we needed to do.</seg>
<seg id="57">Christina didn't speak, but I could see the fear in her eyes.</seg>
<seg id="58">Despite the stark statistics, one positive thing did come from that scan.</seg>
<seg id="59">The doctor revealed that our babies were girls.</seg>
<seg id="60">Christina and Ben had dreamed of being able to stand up at the wedding and announce they were expecting - but it took time to conceive</seg>
<seg id="61">The next day, sick with fear, we arrived at King's College Hospital, South London, and sat in the waiting room, trying to act normally.</seg>
<seg id="62">Professor Kypros Nicolaides is one of the leading specialists in this procedure.</seg>
<seg id="63">If anyone could save our babies, he could.</seg>
<seg id="64">Christina was awake throughout the treatment, and I held her hand tightly as the professor pushed a needle into her abdomen.</seg>
<seg id="65">Within 15 minutes it was over and he waved a scanning wand over Christina's stomach.</seg>
<seg id="66">"They're both alive," he said, before rushing out of the room to his next patient.</seg>
<seg id="67">The next hour, in which we had to wait for a second scan, was torture.</seg>
<seg id="68">But the results promised much.</seg>
<seg id="69">Two heartbeats.</seg>
<seg id="70">Our babies had made it.</seg>
<seg id="71">But this was just the beginning.</seg>
<seg id="72">We would have fortnightly scans, on constant alert for anything that might go wrong.</seg>
<seg id="73">Our nightmare brought us closer together.</seg>
<seg id="74">For the first time, we were genuinely going through something monumental together.</seg>
<seg id="75">We didn't discuss worst-case scenarios with anyone, even though I know both of us were thinking about it.</seg>
<seg id="76">As a man, I felt rather helpless at times.</seg>
<seg id="77">All I could do was try to be supportive and not fuss - a difficult task when you're scared or upset.</seg>
<seg id="78">All I could do was try to be supportive and not fuss - a difficult task when you're scared or upset'</seg>
<seg id="79">One of the hardest things was the waiting.</seg>
<seg id="80">For husbands, a pregnancy already feels interminable.</seg>
<seg id="81">The weeks tick by at a crawl.</seg>
<seg id="82">While your wife can feel it happening, I simply had to watch, never knowing what was going on.</seg>
<seg id="83">By 19 weeks, there were already signs that the smaller twin was not thriving.</seg>
<seg id="84">By 22 weeks, it was revealed that the bigger one appeared to be showing some kind of cardiac problem, the muscle of the heart too large as it desperately tried to pump blood round her system.</seg>
<seg id="85">Our obstetrician said there was nothing we could do but wait.</seg>
<seg id="86">It was up to nature.</seg>
<seg id="87">Just once, before we'd discovered about the twins" condition, we'd visited John Lewis to scout for prams and baby things.</seg>
<seg id="88">This was the start of family life and it felt thrilling.</seg>
<seg id="89">Now we sat quietly at home, not daring to think about changing the spare room into a nursery, refusing to buy baby clothes and gadgets.</seg>
<seg id="90">At the 25-week scan, the doctor began preparing us for the worst.</seg>
<seg id="91">The smaller twin simply wasn't growing.</seg>
<seg id="92">She didn't expect her to make it.</seg>
<seg id="93">Still, somehow, we forced ourselves to hope for the best.</seg>
<seg id="94">The next appointment, at 32 weeks, brought terrible news.</seg>
<seg id="95">By this stage, we'd had more than 20 scans.</seg>
<seg id="96">As the obstetrician moved the paddle over Christina's swollen stomach, we held our breaths.</seg>
<seg id="97">The doctor looked grave.</seg>
<seg id="98">"I'm sorry," she said and, at that moment, our lives changed forever.</seg>
<seg id="99">One of our babies had died.</seg>
<seg id="100">The doctor couldn't tell us precisely when we had lost her, but thought it was probably around 29 or 30 weeks.</seg>
<seg id="101">So that was that.</seg>
<seg id="102">I wouldn't get to meet one of my daughters.</seg>
<seg id="103">Her mother would never get to hold her.</seg>
<seg id="104">Her sister wouldn't play with her.</seg>
<seg id="105">Oddly, I felt blank, like my emotions had fallen into some sort of black-hole.</seg>
<seg id="106">I held my wife as she wept.</seg>
<seg id="107">That evening, I had to write that stark email to our friends.</seg>
<seg id="108">Only then did I break down.</seg>
<seg id="109">We knew we couldn't dwell on our loss.</seg>
<seg id="110">It was crucial that Christina try to stay in as positive a frame of mind as possible for the other baby.</seg>
<seg id="111">We would have to grieve later.</seg>
<seg id="112">Nearly five months on, we have struggled to process our simultaneous emotions of grief and joy</seg>
<seg id="113">When there had been two babies, doctors talked of inducing around 32 weeks, even though it had emerged that the bigger twin had a life-threatening condition called pulmonary stenosis, an obstruction of the artery that carries the blood to the lungs.</seg>
<seg id="114">Soon after she was born, she would need an operation on her heart to insert a balloon into her pulmonary valve to open it up and allow oxygenated blood to flow freely around her system.</seg>
<seg id="115">But after losing one child, the doctors wanted to wait another six or so weeks before inducing to allow the surviving baby the best change of life.</seg>
<seg id="116">Six days before the re-scheduled induction, and ten days before her actual due date, Christina woke up worried that she hadn't felt the baby moving.</seg>
<seg id="117">We rushed to the hospital, but luckily our daughter started kicking again soon after we arrived.</seg>
<seg id="118">Nevertheless, our doctor took one look at our strained, terrified faces and decided it was time for our daughter to come into the world.</seg>
<seg id="119">"Enough stress," she said.</seg>
<seg id="120">Let's get it done.</seg>
<seg id="121">Hannah Valentine Emilie Falk arrived just after 5pm on Wednesday June 12, weighing 7 lbs.</seg>
<seg id="122">We'd named her long ago, just as we had her sister, who we called Rose.</seg>
<seg id="123">Because Hannah was very ill, Christina only got to hold her for a brief time before she was rushed off to the neonatal intensive care baby unit.</seg>
<seg id="124">Rose was delivered soon afterwards.</seg>
<seg id="125">She was tiny, only about 250 grams.</seg>
<seg id="126">We had agreed that we didn't want to see her.</seg>
<seg id="127">We had never met her and wanted to remember her as we'd seen her on the scan, when there was excitement and possibility and joy.</seg>
<seg id="128">The doctors and midwives were wonderful.</seg>
<seg id="129">They asked us carefully about our wishes beforehand, and whisked Rose away once she was born.</seg>
<seg id="130">One of them thoughtfully took a print of Rose's tiny hand and footprints for us.</seg>
<seg id="131">We subsequently framed it and today we keep it in our sitting room, a very private reminder of our little girl.</seg>
<seg id="132">Today, I'm glad we decided not to see her.</seg>
<seg id="133">Now I have a sense of Rose in my head, without any pain attached to my memory.</seg>
<seg id="134">Instead, she is this beautiful idea of a person.</seg>
<seg id="135">Anyone who's been through the excitement and chaos of a birth knows that your head is all over the place.</seg>
<seg id="136">We were so ecstatic about Hannah arriving that it was difficult to think about anything else.</seg>
<seg id="137">Rose was always in the back of our minds, of course, but she was out of our control.</seg>
<seg id="138">At that moment, Hannah was the priority.</seg>
<seg id="139">Two days later, Hannah was transferred to Great Ormond Street Hospital for her heart operation.</seg>
<seg id="140">Christina was stuck at the Whittington because they were worried she had picked up a bacterial infection.</seg>
<seg id="141">It was awful for her to be separated from her daughter and I sent her constant pictures of Hannah by mobile phone, which she loved.</seg>
<seg id="142">I walked with Hannah as they wheeled her down to the operating theatre, her tiny body so innocent and vulnerable.</seg>
<seg id="143">I kissed her forehead as she was given gas to knock her out and I was ushered out of the room.</seg>
<seg id="144">Back upstairs, I sat alone and wept.</seg>
<seg id="145">I wish I could take her place!</seg>
<seg id="146">I sobbed.</seg>
<seg id="147">I'd only met Hannah two days ago, so it felt strange to love someone so much.</seg>
<seg id="148">But in hindsight I can see that wasn't true.</seg>
<seg id="149">From the minute we found out Christina was pregnant, Hannah and I had known each other.</seg>
<seg id="150">Even when she was in the womb, I was her Dad, trying to help her, trying to protect her.</seg>
<seg id="151">Finally, Christina managed to get to Great Ormond Street, having told her doctors she was going whether they liked it or not.</seg>
<seg id="152">For an hour, we sat and hugged and cried and held hands so tightly, they turned white.</seg>
<seg id="153">An eternity later, the surgeon walked in.</seg>
<seg id="154">"It went well," he said and I heard Christina breathe out loudly.</seg>
<seg id="155">She's in recovery, you should be able to see her soon.</seg>
<seg id="156">Small and wan, with eyes that were blue like mine and almond-shaped like her mother's, Hannah blinked up at us from her hospital cot.</seg>
<seg id="157">Her oxygen levels were still low and would remain that way for a while.</seg>
<seg id="158">And she would need another heart operation at some point in the future.</seg>
<seg id="159">But she was beautiful.</seg>
<seg id="160">And she was ours.</seg>
<seg id="161">We brought her home the next week.</seg>
<seg id="162">Rose's funeral took place a fortnight later at the same church where Christina and I were married.</seg>
<seg id="163">At the funeral, I said a few strangled words with our close family standing beside us.</seg>
<seg id="164">Rose was cremated and placed in the same plot as my sister, Anna, who had died in 1980 of cancer when she was four months old.</seg>
<seg id="165">It was important for Christina and me that Rose shared her space with another little girl.</seg>
<seg id="166">After all, she was used to being next to someone else.</seg>
<seg id="167">Anna could keep her company.</seg>
<seg id="168">Nearly five months on, we have struggled to process our simultaneous emotions of grief and joy.</seg>
<seg id="169">We plan to tell Hannah about her sister.</seg>
<seg id="170">By sharing this story, we hope it might help us come to terms with what has happened, and maybe even help couples going through the same situation.</seg>
<seg id="171">Despite all the turmoil, we'd still love to have another child.</seg>
<seg id="172">Sometimes we worry we aren't thinking about Rose enough.</seg>
<seg id="173">It's very hard to grieve for someone you never met.</seg>
<seg id="174">But despite never being born, she did amazing things in the 30 or so weeks she was alive.</seg>
<seg id="175">She made people happy.</seg>
<seg id="176">She made people sad.</seg>
<seg id="177">She was a sister.</seg>
<seg id="178">I'll certainly remember her this way, one of two human-shaped figures in those fuzzy black-and-white scans.</seg>
<seg id="179">It makes me smile to think that on those ultrasounds, she was always on top, looking down at Hannah, making sure she's alright.</seg>
<seg id="180">And then I look at Hannah, as she giggles at us dancing around the kitchen, or laughs while she splashes in the bath and I realise that she's also our reminder of the little girl we lost.</seg>
<seg id="181">And what a magnificent one she is.</seg>
</doc>
