<seg id="5">The WSJ spotted the latest report on VC returns from Cambridge Associates:</seg>
<seg id="6">Their U.S. Venture Capital Index, which is based on data compiled from 1,439 venture capital funds, shows venture capital funds outperforming indices like the Dow Jones Industrial Average only in the short term (the three months to June 30) or the long term (15 or 20 years).</seg>
<seg id="7">For the periods in between, you'd have been better off parking your money in an index fund, although at the ten-year horizon, everyone is about equal.</seg>
<seg id="8">Venture capitalists say the nature of their funds and the way they enter and exit investments means their returns are best judged over longer time periods - five years and upward.</seg>
<seg id="9">Actually, if you compare the VC performance to a proper index, it is even worse than that.</seg>
<seg id="10">Cambridge Associates, which advises and manages money for endowments, presents the VC fund returns as end-to-end Internal Rates of Returns.</seg>
<seg id="11">But it also uses its modified version of the Public Market Equivalent to compare those apples with the oranges of stock market investments.</seg>
