<seg id="1">Coulson used phone hacking to verify tip</seg>
<seg id="2">Former News of the World editor Andy Coulson allegedly used "phone hacking, surveillance and confrontation" in an attempt to confirm a bogus tip about an affair involving then-home secretary Charles Clarke.</seg>
<seg id="3">Prosecutor Andrew Edis QC told the Old Bailey that the News of the World heard a false rumour in May 2005 that Clarke was seeing his "attractive special adviser," Hannah Pawlby.</seg>
<seg id="4">The newspaper tasked private investigator Glenn Mulcaire with hacking Pawlby's voicemails and "door-stepped" her, but Coulson also called and left her voicemails, the court heard.</seg>
<seg id="5">"The prosecution suggests that Mr Coulson, who is now the editor of the NotW, he is not the man who stands outside people's houses hoping to catch them out, he is the man who likes to put the story to people to see what they will say," Mr Edis said.</seg>
<seg id="6">He said the NotW used three ways to investigate stories: phone hacking, surveillance, and confrontation.</seg>
<seg id="7">The editor is personally involved in the third.</seg>
<seg id="8">Obviously he knows about the second, surveillance, he must do.</seg>
<seg id="9">What about the first?</seg>
<seg id="10">Does he know about phone hacking?</seg>
<seg id="11">He says he doesn't, we say "Oh yes, he did".</seg>
<seg id="12">Rumours about an affair involving Clarke were first picked up by the NotW's features desk when a source who was sexually interested in Ms Pawlby was told: "Don't bother wasting your time, she's with Charles."</seg>
<seg id="13">A tape of voicemails taken from her phone on at least three occasions was seized from Mulcaire's home in August 2006.</seg>
<seg id="14">Investigators also found entries on the private investigator's computer which had Ms Pawlby and her sister as "Projects."</seg>
<seg id="15">During the period she was being investigated, Ms Pawlby's grandparents received anonymous calls asking for information about her, Mr Edis said.</seg>
<seg id="16">Meanwhile, former chief reporter Neville Thurlbeck and former reporter James Weatherup oversaw surveillance of Ms Pawlby's movements.</seg>
<seg id="17">Leaving her a voicemail on June 18 2005, Coulson told her: "I've got a story that we're planning to run tomorrow that I really would like to speak to Charles about."</seg>
<seg id="18">Mr Edis said Coulson's involvement in the story followed the same pattern as with other important men, such as former home secretary David Blunkett.</seg>
<seg id="19">The jury heard on Thursday that Coulson confronted Mr Blunkett over an affair with a married woman while he was himself seeing co-defendant Rebekah Brooks, who was married at the time.</seg>
<seg id="20">Coulson and Brooks deny conspiring with others to hack phones between October 3 2000 and August 9 2006.</seg>
<seg id="21">Mulcaire, Thurlbeck and Weatherup have admitted phone hacking.</seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="517103a9024e07faa32fd3365e681df4" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Fahrenheit 45-Fun - NYTimes.com</seg>
<seg id="2">I help run a college TV network that recently held a promotional event where we destroyed a large number of VHS tapes to celebrate an upgrade.</seg>
<seg id="3">The tapes were all either ours (and already digitized) or donated explicitly for the purpose of destroying them.</seg>
<seg id="4">Some people were upset, even publicly comparing it to a book burning.</seg>
<seg id="5">Does it make sense to see a book burning as wrong but a tape smashing as acceptable?</seg>
<seg id="6">Is there a moral component to destroying one's own property?</seg>
<seg id="7">The people who compared your promotional event to a book burning were being either sarcastic or incredibly stupid.</seg>
<seg id="8">There is no relationship between these two activities, outside of how they might appear to a space alien.</seg>
<seg id="9">When people burn books in public, they are symbolically destroying the books" content.</seg>
<seg id="10">Book burning is not problematic because it results in the destruction of paper - it's problematic for advancing the argument that certain ideas should not be allowed to exist.</seg>
<seg id="11">You were not taking a political stand against the use of VHS tape; you were just (playfully) annihilating something that no longer had practical utility.</seg>
<seg id="12">Some might argue that this kind of promotional event is offensive for thoughtlessly satirizing the dark history of book burning, but - here again - such an argument requires a lot of irony or a lot of idiocy.</seg>
<seg id="13">Your second question is a little more complicated.</seg>
<seg id="14">Owning something usually gives you the right to destroy it.</seg>
<seg id="15">No one can stop you from doing so.</seg>
<seg id="16">Most of the time, this is no great loss (because most objects are replaceable).</seg>
<seg id="17">But if something is extremely rare and has value to the rest of society, it's immoral to destroy it without justification.</seg>
<seg id="18">For example, if you came into possession of one of the four original versions of Edvard Munch's "Scream" and decided to burn it for the perverse pleasure of obliterating something precious, you would be acting unethically (and, I suppose, pretty punk rock).</seg>
<seg id="19">You would be destroying something that technically belongs to you alone, but symbolically belongs to the culture at large.</seg>
<seg id="20">The literal destruction of the object itself would create a deeper kind of loss.</seg>
<seg id="21">Obviously, that argument can't be applied to the VHS tapes you smashed, unless one of those tapes contained footage that was aesthetically or socially meaningful, unique to that specific tape and (for whatever reason) impossible to convert into another medium.</seg>
<seg id="22">But I don't think that's what happened.</seg>
<seg id="23">I think you just destroyed a bunch of crap you were never going to use again.</seg>
<seg id="24">I have done a lot of things to the outside of my home to make a burglar look elsewhere for a likely target.</seg>
<seg id="25">I just realized that this means I'm hoping my efforts will make him choose another house in the neighborhood instead of mine.</seg>
<seg id="26">I'm beginning to wonder if this is ethical.</seg>
<seg id="27">If what you've done includes a note that opens, "Dear anonymous criminal: Here is the pass code for my neighbor's home-security system and a schematic blueprint of his residence," then, yes, that's unethical.</seg>
<seg id="28">If you've merely made your home look more forbidding than it actually is (by adding a "Beware of Dog" sign or a motion-sensitive light or a series of N.R.A. placards), you've done nothing untoward to anyone else.</seg>
<seg id="29">You seem to be working from the supposition that there's a 100 percent chance someone on your block is going to be burglarized, and that your protective measures will automatically (and unjustly) shift the crime elsewhere.</seg>
<seg id="30">But even if that were true, what would be the moral alternative?</seg>
<seg id="31">Convincing everyone on your street to unilaterally lock and unlock their doors at the exact same time?</seg>
<seg id="32">It's not unfair to be extra cautious.</seg>
<seg id="33">E-mail queries to ethicist@nytimes.com, or send them to the Ethicist, The New York Times Magazine, 620 Eighth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10018, and include a daytime phone number.</seg>
</doc>
