<seg id="1">Cheaters get high on their dishonesty</seg>
<seg id="2">These people tended to experience a larger boost in positive emotions compared to those who behaved honestly.</seg>
<seg id="3">The findings may help to explain why people will cheat without a good reason and why wealthy celebrities might steal when they have plenty of money to pay for items.</seg>
<seg id="4">Dr Ruedy said: "Many theories of moral behaviour assume that unethical behaviour triggers negative affect."</seg>
<seg id="5">"We challenge this assumption and demonstrate that unethical behaviour can trigger positive affect, which we term a "cheater's high."""</seg>
<seg id="6">The researchers, whose findings are published in the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, conducted six studies on how people felt after cheating.</seg>
<seg id="7">In one 179 students were offered the chance to earn cash rewards for solving anagrams.</seg>
<seg id="8">Forty one per cent of them cheated by adding in solutions after they had seen the answers.</seg>
<seg id="9">The researchers found these cheaters experienced a boost in positive emotions.</seg>
<seg id="10">In another study 161 students were set another challenge where there was no financial reward and on this occasion 68 per cent of these students cheated by clicking on a link to see early answers.</seg>
<seg id="11">Again these cheaters experienced a similar boost in their emotions.</seg>
<seg id="12">In another study to find out why people get this kick, the researchers again recruited 205 people online to solve anagrams and report how they did in return for cash.</seg>
<seg id="13">Some of the participants were sent a message telling them that it would not be possible to check their answers and asking them to report them honestly.</seg>
<seg id="14">Those who lied about their scores and received the message reported greater self-satisfaction than those who cheated but did not receive the message.</seg>
<seg id="15">Dr Ruedy claims this shows that the buzz of cheating comes from the thrill of getting away with it.</seg>
<seg id="16">"She said: "Cheating is associated with feelings of self-satisfaction, and the boost in positive affect from cheating persists even when prospects for self-deception about unethical behaviour are reduced."</seg>
