<seg id="1">Showtime for Bond songs</seg>
<seg id="2">Art: Georgie Pinn.</seg>
<seg id="3">Since Shirley Bassey released Goldfinger almost 50 years ago, it has been tradition for a major artist to record the signature song for each new James Bond film.</seg>
<seg id="4">Now, fans can recognise "Bond songs" from the opening bars alone - even the obscure ones.</seg>
<seg id="5">"They're quite distinct," says Simon Myers, producer of the live stage show The Songs of James Bond.</seg>
<seg id="6">All of them are epic, mysterious, with an element of sex.</seg>
<seg id="7">They have an orchestral background with a rising and falling bass and that guitar line at the start.</seg>
<seg id="8">And singers love them because the vocals are big and challenging and dramatic.</seg>
<seg id="9">Bassey, of course, is the quintessential Bond songstress, having recorded the themes for Goldfinger, Diamonds are Forever and Moonraker.</seg>
<seg id="10">Paul McCartney's Live and Let Die and Carly Simon's Nobody Does It Better were also major hits.</seg>
<seg id="11">Standing alone - stylistically at least - is Madonna's stuttering electro-dance number Die Another Day.</seg>
<seg id="12">"The less said about that, the better," Myers says.</seg>
<seg id="13">These songs can be quite divisive.</seg>
<seg id="14">Some people say Adele's Skyfall is the greatest Bond song of all time; others don't like it at all.</seg>
<seg id="15">And there are those artists you might be surprised to learn have actually recorded Bond songs, like Sheena Easton and Lulu.</seg>
<seg id="16">Maria Mercedes: The glamour endures with Bond songs from the last 50 years.</seg>
<seg id="17">On November 8 and 9, Myers will present 23 of his favourites at Melbourne's Athenaeum Theatre.</seg>
<seg id="18">He has chosen four performers: veteran actor-singer Maria Mercedes; respected vocal coach and singer Susie Ahern; actor and former opera student Ben Mingay; and The Voice finalist Kiyomi Vella.</seg>
<seg id="19">"I've been wanting to do this for 20 years," he says.</seg>
<seg id="20">It started when I bought a CD of James Bond songs and I thought, wouldn't it be awesome to make a concert out of these?</seg>
<seg id="21">Some numbers will performed solo, others as duets, while Live and Let Die will feature all four singers.</seg>
<seg id="22">A 15-piece band will play on stage and visual artist Georgie Pinn will project images onto a giant screen.</seg>
<seg id="23">"It's all original footage that I've shot; there are no scenes from the films," Pinn says.</seg>
<seg id="24">Fire, diamonds, silhouettes: the imagery she has chosen evokes the slick, glamorous feel of the Bond movies.</seg>
<seg id="25">"A lot of it is like the title sequences of the films," she says, "but instead of having the female characters just dancing around, we've given them a more active role."</seg>
<seg id="26">The look and sound of each Bond movie is just as important as the storyline.</seg>
<seg id="27">"I started watching some of the old ones again, to get into the mood," Mercedes says, "and my God, they were so over the top, they were ridiculous!</seg>
<seg id="28">But even if you forget the movies themselves, the songs and the glamour endure.</seg>
<seg id="29">When Mercedes began singing at 14, appearing on various television talent shows, Bassey was her role model.</seg>
<seg id="30">"I listened to her endlessly, singing Goldfinger and Diamonds are Forever," she says.</seg>
<seg id="31">The sophistication, the sexiness - I wanted to be Shirley Bassey.</seg>
<seg id="32">Myers won't reveal who will sing each song but it's a fair bet Mercedes will perform most of Bassey's big numbers.</seg>
<seg id="33">For her, the show's appeal extends beyond the songs.</seg>
<seg id="34">It's a chance for the audience to immerse themselves in mid-century glamour: a world of men in sharp suits and women in sequined dresses, stylish visual projections with a modern twist, and an orchestra taking pride of place on stage.</seg>
<seg id="35">"In this day and age, music often gets sacrificed," Mercedes says.</seg>
<seg id="36">A 15-piece-band is quite a luxury.</seg>
<seg id="37">I've got a black sequined outfit with a split up the side for the first act and a fabulous gold outfit for the second.</seg>
<seg id="38">It's not just a series of songs; it's a show.</seg>
<seg id="39">There's a real sexiness to the whole thing.</seg>
