<seg id="1">Race day: Victoria Derby</seg>
<seg id="2">There is no worse barrier for a horse to draw wide in this country than the 2500-metre start at Flemington, so it's no surprise that bookmakers are now keen to lay the pre-draw equal favourites Savvy Nature and Complacent in Saturday's $1.5 million Victoria Derby after they both drew off the track.</seg>
<seg id="3">Savvy Nature is in gate 13 while Complacent drew even worse with 16.</seg>
<seg id="4">Another top Sydney hope, Criterion, who separated the other two in the Spring Champion Stakes, drew 14.</seg>
<seg id="5">The Victoria Derby barrier was even worse pre 1972 when the VRC finally accepted that the traditional distance of 2400 metres was unfair and it was extended to 2500 metres.</seg>
<seg id="6">The extra 100 metres was added so the three-year-olds had the extra distance before they reached the extremely tight turn out of the straight.</seg>
<seg id="7">Hucklebuck ridden by Dom Tourneur.</seg>
<seg id="8">One might wonder why such a traditional race was run from such a shocking barrier on such a spacious track.</seg>
<seg id="9">Well, the reason is that when the derby was first run in 1885 the Flemington track was quite different with the 2400-metre start being behind the Elms stand, giving the runners an extra 400-metre straight run before they reached the 2000-metre start.</seg>
<seg id="10">Despite the bad draw I still remain confident that the staying-bred Complacent can win the race.</seg>
<seg id="11">Source: Betfair.</seg>
<seg id="12">The Peter Snowden-trained colt is from the first Australian crop of 2007 Epsom Derby winner Authorized, while his dam Insouciance is a daughter of another Epsom Derby winner in Quest For Fame.</seg>
<seg id="13">On that breeding we can all but eliminate any worries about him running the distance and the way he has come on in his Sydney races, finishing with a brilliant win in the Spring Champion Stakes, suggests to me that only bad luck from the bad barrier will prevent him from winning.</seg>
<seg id="14">His main danger might be the Victorian Polanski, who has done everything right in the lead-up and he has drawn perfectly in barrier one.</seg>
<seg id="15">Savvy Nature was OK winning at Moonee Valley last Saturday when he didn't seem happy racing the left-handed way for the first time.</seg>
<seg id="16">But in last week's race he beat a horse who had been beaten at Avoca at his previous start, so I have a query about that form.</seg>
<seg id="17">5 Best Bets</seg>
<seg id="18">Flemington Race 1, No 2 HUCKLEBUCK</seg>
<seg id="19">It's appropriate that on Victoria Derby day a son of 2003 Derby winner Elvstroem looks one of the better bets on the program.</seg>
<seg id="20">This gelding has stamped himself as a serious galloper and getting better as he matures and gets over longer trips.</seg>
<seg id="21">He had a moderate start to his career with an effortless win in a maiden at Gawler then he went to the Morphettville Park track and among those he beat was the recent Geelong Classic winner, Gamblin" Guru.</seg>
<seg id="22">Trainer Phillip Stokes obviously realised he had a horse good enough for the Melbourne spring carnival and, after an unlucky third at Moonee Valley in a strong field, the gelding started favourite at Caulfield and didn't give punters a moment's worry as he strolled home by two lengths.</seg>
<seg id="23">The step up to 1600 metres on Saturday looks ideal.</seg>
<seg id="24">Adelaide gallopers are enjoying a good run here this spring.</seg>
<seg id="25">SUGGESTED BET Back Hucklebuck and start the day on a winning note.</seg>
<seg id="26">Flemington Race 2, No.</seg>
<seg id="27">Darren Weir's home-bred filly May's Dream is a solid favourite to win the VRC Oaks next Thursday and she will firm even more if, as expected, she wins today's Wakeful Stakes and I think that she will.</seg>
<seg id="28">Lightly raced, May's Dream has done everything right in her short career, with an excellent first-up third at Moonee Valley when she looked in need of the run, followed by an easy win at Caulfield, before a gallant second to champion filly Guelph in the Thousand Guineas when she chased that filly hard all the way up the home straight and raced like a true stayer.</seg>
<seg id="29">Being a daughter of South Australian Oaks winner and Melbourne Cup runner-up She's Archie, May's Dream should be ideally suited by today's step up in distance and with Guelph now in the paddock, May's Dream can establish herself as our best staying filly by winning both this and the Oaks.</seg>
<seg id="30">SUGGESTED BET Back May's Dream to win the Wakeful-Oaks double.</seg>
<seg id="31">Flemington Race 4, No.</seg>
<seg id="32">Chris Waller, as well as being Australia's champion trainer, is also a conservative judge of his horses, so when he declared during the week that his star three-year-old Zoustar "might be the next big thing in racing"" he made headlines.</seg>
<seg id="33">Zoustar has since been sold to a leading stud for a $20 million package and may be heading overseas to race at Ascot next year.</seg>
<seg id="34">I've seen Zoustar race in Brisbane and Sydney and I think he'll probably win the Coolmore Stud Stakes today, but while I'm including him in our best bets today, I'm not so sure he is going to be reasonable odds.</seg>
<seg id="35">The hype about him being a $20 million colt has assured that he will be very short, under the odds, and I'm only suggesting him as a betting prospect if we can get black figures.</seg>
<seg id="36">SUGGESTED BET If he wins easily, maybe he's worth $20 million.</seg>
