<seg id="1">Parramatta's Chris Sandow eyes repeat of Broncos demolition</seg>
<seg id="2">Eels' Chris Sandow out to demolish Broncos again.</seg>
<seg id="3">CHRIS Sandow has warned his best is yet to come as the Eels halfback tonight attempts to replicate the demolition job that sparked the Broncos' dramatic freefall last season.</seg>
<seg id="4">The Broncos will start favourites in tonight's clash at Parramatta Stadium, but they are wary of the Sandow threat after the pint-sized playmaker tore them apart in their last meeting at Suncorp Stadium.</seg>
<seg id="5">Sandow scored two tries in the Eels' 42-22 boilover in round 21 last year, including a superb 50-metre solo effort as Brisbane suffered their second defeat in an eventual six-match losing streak.</seg>
<seg id="6">Sandow has battled at times behind a rookie Parramatta pack this season, but he looked more threatening in the Eels' gutsy 14-10 loss at home to North Queensland last week.</seg>
<seg id="7">The 24-year-old admits he is still searching for self-belief after a difficult maiden season at the Eels in 2012 during which he was briefly dumped by former coach Steve Kearney, now an assistant at Brisbane.</seg>
<seg id="8">"I still have more to give," the Kingaroy-born No.7 said.</seg>
<seg id="9">I have to take on the line a bit more and direct the boys around at the same time as well.</seg>
<seg id="10">I needed to get my confidence back (after last season) but I'm happy with the squad we've got, it's a young team and it will take time for us to get better.</seg>
<seg id="11">It was a close game (last week).</seg>
<seg id="12">We made a few errors, I dropped two balls myself and I was filthy with that.</seg>
<seg id="13">I was proud of our effort against the Cowboys, they have an Australian front-row with (James) Tamou and (Matt) Scott, so hopefully we can lift again for the Broncos.</seg>
<seg id="14">Sandow will be ably supported by Eels fullback Jarryd Hayne, who was outstanding against the Cowboys, pulling off three trysaving tackles on Tariq Sims, Gavin Cooper and Tamou.</seg>
<seg id="15">Broncos coach Anthony Griffin warned his side not to be complacent against a Sandow-led Eels side that embarrassed them at Suncorp last season.</seg>
<seg id="16">"We have to get a job done in the middle first before we worry about Sandow and Hayne," Griffin said.</seg>
<seg id="17">You just have to want to tackle him (Sandow).</seg>
<seg id="18">The moment you watch him pass the football he will come at you, he has made a lot of line-breaks this year.</seg>
<seg id="19">He is playing a lot different this year, he is a lot more direct.</seg>
<seg id="20">He is just a real X-factor for them, he is one of those players that does things that other guys can't do with his short kicking game and his running game.</seg>
<seg id="21">Sandow just seems to be very confident and very positive in his decision-making and everything he is doing.</seg>
<seg id="22">This year he is playing a lot more direct and he is backing himself a lot more.</seg>
<seg id="23">To beat Parramatta you've got to do a good job on him.</seg>
<seg id="24">The Broncos received a boost yesterday with veteran forward David Stagg and front-row firebrand Josh McGuire cleared to play.</seg>
<seg id="25">The duo will replace Jarrod Wallace and Scott Anderson, who drop off a six-man bench.</seg>
<seg id="26">"Parramatta have the calibre of players there and it hasn't clicked a few times for them," Broncos centre Jack Reed said.</seg>
<seg id="27">But last year they put 40 points on us, so we have to go down there with the right attitude and treat them with respect.</seg>
</doc>
