<seg id="1">Man banned from the roads after being caught doing double speed limit with cup of tea wedged between his legs</seg>
<seg id="2">Andrew Howie drove his mother's luxury Mercedes Benz E-Class at 130mph to get from Stansted Airport to his home in Tiptree, Essex at 4am</seg>
<seg id="3">He is the director of fresh milkshake company Shaken Udder that stocks for stores including Waitrose, Sainsbury's, Harrods, and Fortnum & Mason</seg>
<seg id="4">The 35-year-old said he was surprised the car didn't have cup holders</seg>
<seg id="5">He received seven points on his licence, a £1,000 fine, and £190 costs</seg>
<seg id="6">Banned: Andrew Howie, 35, here pictured selling his supermarket-stocked milkshakes, has been banned from driving for six months and forced to pay £1,000</seg>
<seg id="7">The director of milkshake company has been banned from driving after he was caught driving at 130mph with a cup of tea wedged between his legs.</seg>
<seg id="8">Andrew Howie, the founder and director of Shaken Udder which sells drinks to Fortnum & Mason, was returning from Stansted Airport after dropping his brother off for a flight when he hit nearly twice the speed limit on the A120.</seg>
<seg id="9">A police patrol car clocked the 35-year-old's speed and chased him down the motorway as he whizzed along in his mother's Mercedes Benz E-Class at 4am.</seg>
<seg id="10">When Howie was eventually pulled over, officers were amazed to see he had a McDonald's cup of tea between his legs.</seg>
<seg id="11">Howie told Colchester Magistrates" Court yesterday he was surprised his mother's luxury car did not have cup holders.</seg>
<seg id="12">Unwilling to sacrifice his morning beverage as he hurtled home, Howie decided on a balancing act.</seg>
<seg id="13">Shaken Udder, which Howie created with his wife, Jodie, sells fresh milkshakes in supermarkets and stores nationwide from Tesco's and Waitrose to Harrods and Whole Foods Market.</seg>
<seg id="14">The drinks are branded as '100 per cent natural' and 'a celebration of good British produce'.</seg>
<seg id="15">After he admitted to careless driving following the incident on May 27, 2013, Howie was handed seven points on his licence and a £1,000 fine.</seg>
<seg id="16">The extra points meant he has now been banned from the roads for six months.</seg>
