<doc docid="dbf4324cf06ba0a9367cf554ab5283fb" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Rugby league Immortal Andrew Johns nervous ahead of More Joyous inquiry</seg>
<seg id="2">Rugby league great Andrew Johns after a surf at Sydney's Whale Beach yesterday.</seg>
<seg id="3">Picture: Attila Szilvasi Source: The Daily Telegraph</seg>
<seg id="4">ANDREW Johns is nervous and so he should be.</seg>
<seg id="5">Don't worry about his State of Origin career.</seg>
<seg id="6">Today is one of the most pressurised days of his life.</seg>
<seg id="7">Johns' moment of reckoning arrives today when he will attend the second day of the More Joyous hearing, and his performance may be remembered ahead of any game of football he ever played.</seg>
<seg id="8">The former rugby league great has moved in so many different directions since the story broke he could hide behind a corkscrew.</seg>
<seg id="9">Johns has reportedly become acutely stressed at what lies ahead, and you can understand it because he has already told two different versions of his conversation with bookie Tom Waterhouse about the prospects of More Joyous in the All Aged Stakes.</seg>
<seg id="10">That spells trouble today, because no matter what line he chooses, he will poke a hole in one of his earlier defences.</seg>
<seg id="11">But saving face cannot be his priority.</seg>
<seg id="12">Today racing deserves the truth.</seg>
<seg id="13">Take it as read that whoever he supports owner John Singleton or bookmaker Tom Waterhouse his friendship with the other will be ruined beyond repair.</seg>
<seg id="14">Like many high-profile team sportsmen, Johns has spent much of his life in a bubble where his mess has been cleaned up by others.</seg>
<seg id="15">Few Sydneysiders are better connected.</seg>
<seg id="16">Despite the rule that claims off-field deeds don't matter, no other player would survive a drug addiction and a racism scandal to be judged an Immortal.</seg>
<seg id="17">For once he cannot say "sort it out with my manager" or "go and see the chief executive" the eternal cop-out lines of football stars backed into tight corners.</seg>
<seg id="18">He started the bushfire about More Joyous being "off" and now he is out there on his own, the world is closing in fast, and he has some serious questions to answer.</seg>
<seg id="19">Singleton yesterday turned the heat up on Johns by claiming he told him More Joyous would "finish nearer last than first" which she did.</seg>
<seg id="20">In contrast to the world of rugby league stardom, where players can hide behind iron curtains erected by their clubs, racing folk are used to being isolated, exposed and vulnerable, and it's why several other big players in this soap opera have handled the pressure better than Johns.</seg>
<seg id="21">Every racing person is an island buffeted by the gale-force winds of a volatile industry, and it breeds tough people.</seg>
<seg id="22">Most horses never win a dollar.</seg>
<seg id="23">Most tips fail.</seg>
<seg id="24">Most trainers end up near broke.</seg>
<seg id="25">In the Bible, the meek inherit the Earth.</seg>
<seg id="26">In racing, they get swallowed whole.</seg>
<seg id="27">You wouldn't call racing legends classical role models, but it's easy to admire their cement coating.</seg>
<seg id="28">Mega-rich owner Singleton could have afforded 10 lawyers if he wanted to, but he represented himself at the inquiry because he wanted his message alone to get through.</seg>
<seg id="29">His performance was not flawless, and most felt he was the loser on the day, but in some ways that made his decision to roll the dice and go it alone even braver.</seg>
<seg id="30">In the other corner, Gai Waterhouse hired a posse of lawyers and she has had some impressive moments too under great duress since the scandal broke.</seg>
<seg id="31">The racing world has learnt more about Gai in the past few weeks than we have in the last few decades.</seg>
<seg id="32">We always wondered who exactly was the real person beneath the plum accent who routinely tipped everything bar her clothes horse as "an exceptional winning charrrrrnce."</seg>
<seg id="33">Now we know.</seg>
<seg id="34">She is tough, combative and deceptively cunning, a true perfumed steamroller who will fight to the death for herself and her family.</seg>
<seg id="35">Her masterstroke at the first day of the inquiry was to wait until the final hour late in the day to unveil her killer lines "You're a sham, John," and "We're here because of Chinese whispers (between) a trumped-up little jockey, a brothel owner and a football player."</seg>
<seg id="36">It ensured she provided the freshest meat for the television news and the next morning's paper.</seg>
<seg id="37">Had she been a footballer, she may have been withdrawn from a commitment speaking to a lunch for 500 at the Warrnambool jumps carnival a few days after the scandal broke.</seg>
