<seg id="1">System can survive self-managed funds' property move</seg>
<seg id="2">SMSF trustees have been accused of causing a housing price bubble.</seg>
<seg id="3">Picture: Sam Mooy Source: TheAustralian</seg>
<seg id="4">THE one million-plus Australians who invest via a self-managed super fund may have been getting concerned recently that their desire to take control of their retirement savings plans had made them financial saboteurs.</seg>
<seg id="5">SMSF trustees have been accused of pumping up a residential property price bubble or exploiting tax loopholes to gain an unfair advantage - or both.</seg>
<seg id="6">But they are not going to bring the Australian financial system to its knees any time soon.</seg>
<seg id="7">Indeed, the Reserve Bank's Financial Stability Report in September noted for the first time that SMSFs are a significant segment of our financial system and an important barometer of household financial health.</seg>
<seg id="8">Oddly, there is a tendency to demonise the role of SMSFs within the broader super industry, the same industry that bemoans the lack of engagement by members with their superannuation.</seg>
<seg id="9">The residential property market in Australia is more than $4 trillion in size.</seg>
<seg id="10">At June 30, according to tax office data, SMSF property investments were worth $76 billion, of which $58 billion was commercial property.</seg>
<seg id="11">Residential property investment within the SMSFs is a much more modest $17.5 billion, which makes it hard to reconcile how it could move market values, given the size of the overall market.</seg>
<seg id="12">The bubble speculation also ignores the basic fact that SMSFs are simply the vehicle individuals invest through.</seg>
<seg id="13">The same people could just as easily negatively gear to buy a property outside the super system.</seg>
<seg id="14">The Reserve Bank is responsible for our financial system's stability, so it is entirely reasonable that it raises awareness where it sees the potential for risks to emerge.</seg>
<seg id="15">The RBA was clear that "this sector does not currently pose material risks to financial stability," but its concern comes from SMSFs being "a new source of demand that could possibly exacerbate property price cycles."</seg>
<seg id="16">What keeps a central banker awake at night is seeing household debt increasing faster than incomes, particularly where banks may be relaxing lending standards in order to gain or maintain market share.</seg>
<seg id="17">SMSFs can certainly help inform the RBA about the level of savings and/or financial stress within a major segment of Australian households.</seg>
<seg id="18">The red flag that the RBA raised was the increasing opportunity for - and promotion of - gearing within SMSFs to buy property.</seg>
<seg id="19">This is a relatively new phenomenon.</seg>
<seg id="20">Clearly the banking sector has responded to the perceived demand from SMSFs buying property both by developing new product offers and by increasing promotion of their offers.</seg>
<seg id="21">The latest Vanguard/Investment Trends survey of SMSF investors in April showed that less than 6 per cent were using borrowed funds to invest in residential property, while about 30 per cent of people intending to set up an SMSF wanted to invest in property.</seg>
<seg id="22">The issue here is not so much that SMSFs may be buying property but rather the advice, or lack of it, that they are getting when making that decision.</seg>
<seg id="23">The figures do not support the notion that SMSFs are rushing headlong into residential property.</seg>
<seg id="24">Indeed, 83 per cent of respondents said their next investment was destined to be shares.</seg>
<seg id="25">But Google SMSF and property and you will find pages of material clamouring to tempt SMSF investors to buy property.</seg>
<seg id="26">The simple fact for people considering setting up an SMSF is that if you are doing it just to buy a residential property, there are many simpler ways to do that.</seg>
<seg id="27">If the public swirl around SMSF investment trends prompts investors to review and question their SMSF's portfolio, that is a good outcome.</seg>
<seg id="28">But where the public swirl has raised concerns or caused anxiety, the best antidote is to seek advice from a licensed adviser with specialist training and qualifications in the SMSF world.</seg>
<seg id="29">Robin Bowerman is head of market strategy and communications at fund manager Vanguard Investments Australia.</seg>
</doc>
