<seg id="1">Tipping Points - NYTimes.com</seg>
<seg id="2">I recently moved to the mecca of small coffee shops.</seg>
<seg id="3">Many have tip jars on the counter.</seg>
<seg id="4">When I receive my change, I usually drop the coins into the jar.</seg>
<seg id="5">I figure this is better than no tip at all, and I don't like carrying lots of change.</seg>
<seg id="6">But it occurs to me that this may come across as cheap and insulting.</seg>
<seg id="7">If I were a barista, I might not want a customer's dimes and pennies.</seg>
<seg id="8">Should I tip?</seg>
<seg id="9">And if so, only with dollar bills?</seg>
<seg id="10">Zoe, Manhattan</seg>
<seg id="11">Whatever you do, do not investigate this question on the Internet or listen to more than three versions (in a row) of "Pennies From Heaven," which has been sung by everyone from Billie Holiday to Regis Philbin.</seg>
<seg id="12">It's an hour of your life you will never get back, and the song will make you want to slap someone.</seg>
<seg id="13">People have lots to say about tip jars.</seg>
<seg id="14">Let me synthesize: Baristas are typically paid minimum wage, unlike waiters in restaurants (who are often paid less because of the tips we leave them).</seg>
<seg id="15">Many people take this as a strong argument against tip jars.</seg>
<seg id="16">But I suspect these same folks have never tried to subsist on minimum wage or worked gigs where less than full-time employment is the norm.</seg>
<seg id="17">Tipping lives at the crossroads of social custom and personal choice.</seg>
<seg id="18">Traditionally, we don't leave tips on over-the-counter transactions.</seg>
<seg id="19">But this is changing, because of the more personalized services being offered (marked by such words as "skinny" and "no-foam") and the harsh realities of our economy.</seg>
<seg id="20">I prefer to err on the side of generosity - by which I do not mean three pennies of change on your $2.97 latte.</seg>
<seg id="21">Toss the pennies into the jar and dig up another quarter (or two).</seg>
<seg id="22">Heck, make it a crisp dollar bill, if you can swing it and feel like it.</seg>
<seg id="23">If everyone added a few dimes, a worker's wages might grow by a few bucks over her shift.</seg>
<seg id="24">If you want to limit your tip to the change you receive (or skip the tip), that's your choice, too.</seg>
<seg id="25">Just don't claim the exorbitant cost of your caffeinated confection as an excuse.</seg>
<seg id="26">The people serving you do not take a cut of the revenue.</seg>
<seg id="27">Yes, Thanks, I'm Tall</seg>
<seg id="28">My 9-year-old son is tall for his age.</seg>
<seg id="29">When adults learn how old he is, they often say: "Wow!"</seg>
<seg id="30">You're tall.</seg>
<seg id="31">Although this seems like a compliment, it is awkward to reply: "Thank you."</seg>
<seg id="32">So my son mumbles agreement.</seg>
<seg id="33">We'd like to find a polite reply for him.</seg>
<seg id="34">And why is it O.K. to comment on height, but not other physical characteristics?</seg>
<seg id="35">Beth, Darien, CT</seg>
<seg id="36">Ninety percent of what (irrelevant) adults say to children is idiotic, and most of it involves their size: "You've grown a foot since last month!" and "What a big girl you are!"</seg>
<seg id="37">I don't know how they bear it.</seg>
<seg id="38">Arm your son with a pat response: "Yes, I'm the second tallest boy in my class."</seg>
<seg id="39">Of course, you are correct: It is a bad idea to comment on people's physical characteristics.</seg>
<seg id="40">But when it comes to males and height, something in our pioneer stock (or Darwinian natural selection) makes tallness a reliably good trait.</seg>
<seg id="41">You may verify this with any gentleman 5-foot-8 or shorter.</seg>
<seg id="42">Nice to Be Noticed</seg>
<seg id="43">A friend and I went to visit a relative at the retirement home where she lives.</seg>
<seg id="44">As we were eating in the dining hall, we were interrupted about 10 times by other residents who stopped to say hello (and satisfy their curiosity about who we were).</seg>
<seg id="45">Each time, our hostess introduced us and a short chat ensued.</seg>
<seg id="46">After a while, I began to feel annoyed with her for allowing these disruptions.</seg>
<seg id="47">I know she has to live with these people, but couldn't she have handled the situation better?</seg>
<seg id="48">Anonymous</seg>
<seg id="49">Welcome to the world of the dashing Hemsworth brothers, whom everyone wants to meet (though practically no one knows which is Chris and which is Liam).</seg>
<seg id="50">Short of being brusque with her fellow residents, whose lives are probably not chockablock with visitors, I don't see what your friend could have done differently.</seg>
<seg id="51">Try recasting your irritation as kindness to your friend and her elderly neighbors.</seg>
<seg id="52">And next time, if it's privacy you want, spring for a meal at a nearby restaurant (or chai lattes to enjoy in her room).</seg>
<seg id="53">The Uninvited</seg>
<seg id="54">My childhood best friend just got married.</seg>
<seg id="55">I was surprised that I was not invited to the wedding, but I only see him every couple of years, so I don't blame his prioritizing more current friends.</seg>
<seg id="56">I would like to congratulate him, but I worry that I will make him feel guilty for not inviting me.</seg>
<seg id="57">How should I handle this?</seg>
<seg id="58">Anonymous, New York</seg>
<seg id="59">Good for you to wonder how your call might be received.</seg>
<seg id="60">Now start dialing.</seg>
<seg id="61">Wedding lists are fraught with space and financial considerations and lunacy of nearly every stripe.</seg>
<seg id="62">But they rarely have anything to do with us.</seg>
<seg id="63">Your friend has nothing to feel guilty for.</seg>
<seg id="64">So, be the good guy you are.</seg>
<seg id="65">I know he'll appreciate hearing from you.</seg>
<seg id="66">For help with your awkward situation, send a question to SocialQ@nytimes.com or SocialQ on Facebook.</seg>
<seg id="67">You can also address your queries on Twitter to @SocialQPhilip.</seg>
<seg id="68">Please list a daytime phone number.</seg>
</doc>
