<seg id="1">Office towers' future resides in apartments</seg>
<seg id="2">AS the residential upturn gathers pace, expect to see a rash of older and less efficient office buildings converted into apartment towers.</seg>
<seg id="3">House price growth is strong, with capital city values rising 3.4 per cent in the three months to October 31, according to RP Data-Rismark, with home loan volumes up and building approvals on the rise.</seg>
<seg id="4">The market is also being underpinned by population growth, a shortage of dwellings and low interest rates.</seg>
<seg id="5">Meanwhile, investor interest is particularly strong.</seg>
<seg id="6">The latest available data shows that lending to investors for residential dwellings rose by nearly 26 per cent in the year to August.</seg>
<seg id="7">That is the fastest pace of growth in nearly six years.</seg>
<seg id="8">Office towers in the western corridor of the Sydney CBD have already piqued developers' interest.</seg>
<seg id="9">Jones Lang LaSalle and Knight Frank are marketing an office building at 286 Sussex Street.</seg>
<seg id="10">The tower, managed by Cornerstone Properties, could trade for more than $45 million, after being bought in 2011 for $32.5m.</seg>
<seg id="11">Designs by architects Crone Partners suggest the site could sustain about 180 apartments.</seg>
<seg id="12">Foreign investors are also jumping on this trend, especially Asian-backed groups.</seg>
<seg id="13">Separately, the Blackstone-owned Valad Property Group is reported to be close to selling its 227 Elizabeth Street office building to an offshore developer.</seg>
<seg id="14">The 23-storey B-grade property with approval for 114 units is expected to sell for around $145m, well ahead of initial expectations of $120m.</seg>
<seg id="15">Earlier this year, China's Greenland Group snapped up the former Sydney Water Board site in Bathurst Street for a $600m project including what will be the city's tallest apartment tower.</seg>
<seg id="16">Traditional demand for office towers is heavily linked to white-collar employment.</seg>
<seg id="17">The jobs market is subdued, particularly for full-time work, with employment growth likely to remain modest over the coming year, causing the office vacancy rate to drift higher.</seg>
<seg id="18">Office space net absorption for next year is likely to be below the long-term average.</seg>
<seg id="19">The ageing of Australia's office stock and subdued jobs growth means conversions of older and lower grade office buildings are opportunities being embraced, especially where demand for residential apartments is strongest.</seg>
<seg id="20">Besa Deda is chief economist with St George Bank.</seg>
</doc>
