<seg id="1">Police nab more than 100 drivers in five-hour blitz using new numberplate recognition technology</seg>
<seg id="2">A DRUG-fuelled learner driver caught behind the wheel of a stolen vehicle and a motorcyclist cruising in a bicycle lane are among more than 100 road users nabbed during a five-hour police blitz in Melbourne's southwest.</seg>
<seg id="3">Two road users were also found driving after having their licences cancelled, five failed to even hold a licence and nine had suspended licences.</seg>
<seg id="4">Police also detected 22 unregistered vehicles as part of the operation.</seg>
<seg id="5">State Highway Patrol members used new automatic numberplate recognition technology to check more than 5000 cars as they drove past their post on Point Cook Rd in Seabrook between 1pm and 5pm on Wednesday.</seg>
<seg id="6">Police revealed the details of the road policing exercise on the same day it unveiled its latest weapon to crackdown on road users flouting the law - four new police vehicles boasting numberplate recognition cameras.</seg>
<seg id="7">Each police car will have cameras mounted on the front, back and roof.</seg>
<seg id="8">The vehicles will be based at Frankston, Shepparton, Geelong and Brimbank.</seg>
<seg id="9">Top traffic cop Assistant Commissioner Bob Hill said the new police cars are a quick and effective way to catch drivers doing the wrong thing.</seg>
<seg id="10">"Rather than waiting for the vehicles to come to you, we can deploy to our hotpots utilising the mobilised equipment and we can move it around," he said.</seg>
<seg id="11">A member utilising the mobilised technology can read, in a six or seven hour period, about 5,000 plates.</seg>
<seg id="12">Police have warned they will saturate roads over the Melbourne Cup carnival.</seg>
</doc>
<doc docid="fd3223cd251f74ff1740cdd17f376035" genre="news" origlang="xx">
<seg id="1">Challenging the status quo - Telegraph</seg>
<seg id="2">Spotify may have 10 million tracks but what the mass market really wants is great music, well curated.</seg>
<seg id="3">If you want to create the best music playlist of all time, it will be made up of the songs people have bought over the last 60 years, which is the charts.</seg>
<seg id="4">I Like Music makes a healthy £1.5m turnover working with publishers across the world - it has an exclusive contract to supply the BBC with music for its programme content across TV, radio and online.</seg>
<seg id="5">"We supply 10,000 users at the BBC," explains Hill.</seg>
<seg id="6">The B2B market pays the bills.</seg>
<seg id="7">But I Like Music goes beyond pure licensing.</seg>
<seg id="8">It has developed a raft of products that allows it to work with third parties to add value to music so that punters want to pay for tracks.</seg>
<seg id="9">One deal, with card maker Funky Pigeon, adds a QR code to birthday cards allowing the recipient to play The Soundtrack of Your Life.</seg>
<seg id="10">"It's a streamed version of every number one from every one of your birthdays," says Hill.</seg>
<seg id="11">Another innovation is the Virtual Jukebox.</seg>
<seg id="12">"Anyone with a mobile phone can walk into a bar, scan a code or visit a url, and up comes a jukebox," explains Hill.</seg>
<seg id="13">You select tracks on your phone and it plays in the bar.</seg>
<seg id="14">Four of the UK's leading brewers have already signed up and I Like Music is in the process of signing a trade deal with a Chicago-based distributor too.</seg>
<seg id="15">"Bars don't have a £2,000 jukebox on the wall so there's nothing for drunken punters to punch or kick," says Hill.</seg>
<seg id="16">They just get a little box from us.</seg>
<seg id="17">I Like Music has been playing it safe with the B2B market in recent years but Hill is about to make his first foray into the consumer market.</seg>
<seg id="18">He has secured a £750,000 loan from Santander, and plans to launch a pop up shop in Brick Lane to sell a range of I Like Music merchandise, and a series of products for the gifting market.</seg>
<seg id="19">"We are creating a gift card with an annual subscription so that if you enter any date, you get that week's chart hits," he says.</seg>
<seg id="20">We also have t-shirts, bags and hats that feature a QR code that streams a curated playlist.</seg>
<seg id="21">Gifting is the sweet spot, he argues.</seg>
<seg id="22">You don't want to give someone a dodgy track you've downloaded from Limewire for their birthday.</seg>
<seg id="23">This new revenue stream is forecast to increase turnover threefold by 2016.</seg>
<seg id="24">"The only way to reinvigorate this industry is to innovate," says Hill.</seg>
<seg id="25">If you're bringing added value to music then people will buy it.</seg>
<seg id="26">Publishing industry rebound</seg>
<seg id="27">The printed book market continues to decline while the worldwide e-reader market (including the ubiquitous Kindle) is estimated to hit over $6bn in revenue by 2014.</seg>
<seg id="28">Three authors have joined forces to take a second look at the tired book publishing industry, and place the power back in the hands of authors and readers.</seg>
<seg id="29">Unbound was launched by Dan Kieran, John Mitchinson (the creator of the QI series) and Justin Pollard in 2011.</seg>
<seg id="30">The company allows authors to pitch ideas for books and runs a crowdfunding platform where supporters can offer their financial backing.</seg>
<seg id="31">The firm has funded 50 new books to date, with over £1m pledged.</seg>
<seg id="32">Dan Kieran believes that this model could truly be the salvation of the publishing industry.</seg>
<seg id="33">"Most publishers don't really know who reads their books," he says.</seg>
<seg id="34">They just publish the ones they know retailers will stock.</seg>
<seg id="35">They often aren't willing to take a risk on left field projects.</seg>
<seg id="36">In contrast, Unbound's projects only come to life once the readers themselves lend their backing.</seg>
<seg id="37">Kieran has found that once people want to read a book, they are willing to put up a fair wedge of cash.</seg>
<seg id="38">"The average pledge price is £35, which is seven times the average price of a book," he says.</seg>
<seg id="39">One author, Dr Sue Black, raised £30,000 in three days.</seg>
<seg id="40">Authors are flocking to the company in droves because of its unique profit share model.</seg>
<seg id="41">The split is 50/50, whether you're a first time writer or an established author.</seg>
<seg id="42">In traditional publishing, royalties stand at 5pc-10pc.</seg>
<seg id="43">"The average author earns £14,000 a year but if you take out the JK Rowlings and Stephen Kings, that drops to just £4,000," explains Kieran.</seg>
<seg id="44">Part of the appeal of an Unbound book is the workmanship.</seg>
<seg id="45">"We're not giving 65pc of the cover price to the retailer so our books are incredibly beautiful," says Kieran.</seg>
<seg id="46">This is part of the secret to ensuring that books stay in vogue, he argues.</seg>
<seg id="47">My son is eight and can't stand digital books.</seg>
<seg id="48">He sleeps with his favbourites under his pillow.</seg>
<seg id="49">You wouldn't do that with a Kindle.</seg>
<seg id="50">Betting on customer service</seg>
<seg id="51">Back in the golden age of bookmaking, well-to-do gentlemen would visit their bookies in Mayfair, Park Lane and Carnaby Street to place bets on the horses, collect winnings and engage in some spirited repartee.</seg>
<seg id="52">Some of today's biggest gambling houses have their roots in this private service: William Hill had an off-track betting shop in Park Lane in the thirties.</seg>
<seg id="53">Now one entrepreneur is looking to bring back that personalised service through bespoke bookmakers Fitzdares.</seg>
<seg id="54">Balthazar Fabricius founded the company in 20006 and took his first bet in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="55">Today, his firm boasts 1,200 members and placed £88m in fixed odds bets last year.</seg>
<seg id="56">"Most betting shops today are corporate monolithic businesses," says Fabricius.</seg>
<seg id="57">They have become gaming operators with online casinos and bingo betting emporiums.</seg>
<seg id="58">There is a demand for a high level of service.</seg>
<seg id="59">That the original customer has been forgotten.</seg>
<seg id="60">Fabricius has brought back the telephone betting model, with a twist.</seg>
<seg id="61">"The market all thought we were mad," he says.</seg>
<seg id="62">It was the one part of everyone's business that was declining.</seg>
<seg id="63">But if you swap the word telephone for mobile, that's actually the one part of every bookmakers that's growing exponentially.</seg>
<seg id="64">We pioneered text message betting.</seg>
<seg id="65">By giving each member an exclusive phone number and a dedicated bookie, Fabricius brought back the old world charm of gambling.</seg>
<seg id="66">He also introduced a series of perks for his customers, from top seats at an Eric Clapton concert in Floridita to free bets on their birthdays.</seg>
<seg id="67">"We gave a £5,000 free bet to one guy the other day," he said.</seg>
<seg id="68">He just couldn't believe it.</seg>
<seg id="69">There are no membership fees, but Fitzdares only opens accounts through referral.</seg>
<seg id="70">New customers are tempted in by Fitzdares prices: "We operate the John Lewis model of never being knowingly undersold," says Fabricius.</seg>
<seg id="71">And an active social media profile across Twitter, Facebook, Pinterest and the company blog has drawn in a much younger audience than the original "British horse racing" member.</seg>
<seg id="72">Fancy a flutter on Strictly Come Dancing or a punt on the Ashes at 2am?</seg>
<seg id="73">Fitzdares will accommodate.</seg>
</doc>
